review_body:
Absolutely purrrfect is how I’d describe this book for me! After blitzing myself on short stories to wrap up my 2014 reading goal, I was ready for something with more substance and found much more than I expected in this wonderful story. The blurb caught my attention and I expected to enjoy this one, but I was delighted to get far more than I bargained for. Not only does trouble come in threes, but apparently perfection does too. Here are three of the primary things I loved about this book:

1. Topping the list are the characters. Each character was unique and vivid with strong identifiable personalities. Kirk had a quirky sense of humor that kept me in smiles throughout the story. Most of all, however, I adored the cat behavior the author was able to describe about Dolf and Tal that felt so true-to-life – from the playfulness, to the slinking, to the graceful moves, to the rubbing and head butts, to the loud purring that sounds like a running motor – I could see and feel them as if they were right there.

2. The ménage connection between Kirk, Dolf and Tal. I happen to love threesomes, but many people have trouble believing that threesomes can be viable long-term relationships. This threesome felt very believable. It was clear that Kirk provided not only a balance between Dolf and Tal, but filled in missing pieces for both as well. And despite being fated mates (at least on Dolf and Tal’s part for Kirk), the connection and certainly the romance were not givens (insta-lust perhaps, but not insta-love); this relationship required work and convincing. The sex, on the other hand, was natural and holy smokin’ hot from the get go with just a wee little bit of kinky spanking thrown in to spice things up!

3. The entire storyline was unique and intriguing. It was paranormal with a twist – not only in having shifters able to take on the form of domestic house cats, but also in the whole bonding with a human ritual and outcome. Instead of issues around homophobia, this story had a whole other level of human phobia going on. And last, but not least, the mystery in this one truly kept me guessing until the very end.

I’m not really even a cat person, but I could totally be converted after reading this awesome story. As I said, purrrfect and highly recommended!outcome. Instead of issues around homophobia, this story had a whole other level of human phobia going on. And last, but not least, the mystery in this one truly kept me guessing until the very end.

I’m not really even a cat person, but I could totally be converted after reading this awesome story. As I said, purrrfect and highly recommended!

review_headline: Great animated gift card! :) ... bad email delivery :(
review_body: Great video gift card - very funny.  Sent this to my 15 year old niece, who loved the animation.  I have no criticism with the video card itself only that when I initially sent to my niece's email, it never went through.  I tried re-sending it to her at another email address and again it never went through. I called Amazon customer service, and the agent tried to resend it again to my niece's 2 email addresses - same results.  Finally, the agent sent it to MY email address, and success!  I then had to forward it to my niece, who got it 1 week after the Christmas Eve date I had originally scheduled it to be delivered to her.    Also, I never got an email confirming that the card had been sent or that it was viewed by my intended recipient.  I only got an email a few days prior to my desired delivery date stating \\"This is a confirmation of your scheduled gift card order. The gift card(s) below will be delivered on Dec 24, 2014\\" - the date I chose to have it delivered.    On the same day I ordered this gift card from Amazon, I also ordered my niece a Starbucks email gift card, and likewise scheduled it to be delivered on Christmas Eve.  Starbucks sent me emails confirming that the e-gift card had been delivered and also that it had been viewed by her - aahh...peace of mind.  With the Amazon e-gift card, I had to check my account and even when I did, the status only said that it was sent.  Had I not asked my niece if she the gift card was in her inbox, I wouldn't have known that it never got to her.      Had it not been for the delivery issue, I would give this 5 stars.
Well, give me $10 to not receive

I think Amazon need to make vouchers usable no matter what country they are in.

product_title: Amazon Gift Card - Print - Amazon Boxes
review_headline: Why am I writing a review for this? No reason. Seriously, no reason to write a review for a gift card.
review_body: Wow! What a great idea! A Gift card! For to give as a gift! I give this idea and card 5 stars!    OK, sarcasm aside, Amazon might want to re-think having reviews for every damn thing on their website. It's a gift card - one (small) step above shoving a couple of $20.00's into someones hand and saying \\"Go buy something you like\\", or \\"Tell your Mom I had a great time last night\\". How is this even reviewable? For the design? There's a lot of design options, and none of them are anything special (Sorry creative team, someone had to tell you). One thing I should point out is, across all gift cards purchased in the US, an average of 20% of them go unused. So, in other words, if you spend $100.00 on a gift card, consider it a $20.00 gift to Amazon. It's not Amazons fault - any retailer would be stupid not to get that kind of crazy easy money. Just make sure that the person you give it to is actually going to use it. And if you can think of anything else, literally anything up to and including cash, just give that.
